# Normalize every text file to LF in the repository (bug-065). Release zips are
# built with `git archive`, which ships blob bytes verbatim for paths with no
# `text` attribute — so any file committed WITH CRLF stayed CRLF in the shipped
# artifact no matter what `core.eol`/`core.autocrlf` were set to at archive time.
# CRLF in a release is functionally benign on Dispatcharr's Linux host (Python
# reads it fine, and it is NOT the bug-087 backslash-path issue that breaks
# install), but it violates the LF convention and defeats byte-identical
# vendoring. `text=auto` lets git detect and leave binaries alone.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Belt and braces: never touch these, whatever the auto-detection thinks.
*.png binary
*.zip binary

# The git hook is executed by bash; CRLF would break it (\r: command not found).
.githooks/pre-commit text eol=lf
*.sh text eol=lf

# The vendored shared core is sha256-pinned by tests/test_core_parity.py against
# scripts/core_manifest.json, so it MUST stay LF on every OS — a CRLF checkout
# (Windows autocrlf) would change the hash and break the drift gate. Same for any
# future vendored shared file.
matching_core.py text eol=lf
aliases_base.py text eol=lf
